#!/usr/bin/env perl

use strict;
use warnings;

use File::Basename qw(basename);
use File::Spec;
use FindBin qw($Bin);

my $command = basename($0);
my $core = File::Spec->catfile( $Bin, '_dashboard-core' );
exec { $^X } $^X, $core, $command, @ARGV;
die "Unable to exec $core for $command: $!";

__END__

=pod

=head1 NAME

stop - private built-in command wrapper for Developer Dashboard

=head1 SYNOPSIS

  dashboard stop

=head1 DESCRIPTION

This private helper is staged under F<~/.developer-dashboard/cli/dd/> so the
public C<dashboard> entrypoint can stay a thin switchboard.

=for comment FULL-POD-DOC START

=head1 PURPOSE

This staged helper exposes C<dashboard stop>, which stops the managed web listener and coordinated collectors for the current runtime while showing a visible terminal task board during interactive runs.

=head1 WHY IT EXISTS

It exists because runtime shutdown is a built-in operational command, but the public switchboard should dispatch to a helper while the runtime manager owns pid validation and stop ordering.

=head1 WHEN TO USE

Use this file when changing stop CLI behavior or the handoff into the runtime lifecycle manager.

=head1 HOW TO USE

Users run C<dashboard stop>. The staged helper forwards the request into the private runtime, which prints the full stop task list on C<stderr> for interactive terminals, stops the web process and the collectors associated with the active runtime, and leaves the final JSON payload on C<stdout>.

=head1 WHAT USES IT

It is used by operators shutting down the local dashboard, by integration smoke that verifies the runtime really stops listening, and by runtime manager tests.

=head1 EXAMPLES

Example 1:

  dashboard stop

Run the public built-in command path that stages or re-enters this helper.

Example 2:

  ~/.developer-dashboard/cli/dd/stop --help

Inspect the staged helper directly after C<dashboard init> or helper extraction has populated the home runtime.

Example 3:

  prove -lv t/05-cli-smoke.t t/30-dashboard-loader.t

Rerun the focused staged-helper and thin-loader tests after changing helper dispatch behavior.

Example 4:

  prove -lr t

Verify that the helper still behaves correctly inside the complete repository suite.


